Preprint   Journal XX (XXXX) XXXXXX  https://doi.org/XXXX/XXXX   xxxx -xxxx/xx/xxxxxx  1    A Synthetic Macroscopic Magnetic Unipole   Emmanouil Markoulakis1, John Chatzakis1, Ant hony Konstantaras1 and Emmanuel Antonidakis1  1 Department  of Electronic Engineering , Computer Technology Informatics & Electronic Devices  Laboratory, Hel lenic Mediterranean University , Chania, Greece     E-mail: markoul@hmu.gr     Received 18 May 2020 , Revised 27 July 2020   Accepted for publication 14 August 2020   Published online 14 August 2020   Abstract   We demonstrate experimentally with a prototype for the first time, that an artificial emergent magnetic unipole hedgehog  field in a simply connected three -dimensional domain is possible, emulating effectively the Dirac model by simply using  a  novel  perma nent magnets ’ topology and geometrical arrangement in a ring array.
printer files for prototype version 3 can be found in this link,  https://tinyurl.com/ycw9uf5p .

We can count here the discrete   24 poles of the array  on the perimeter  and also observe the  emergent unipole vortex forming at the center of the hole  similar to a screw and apparently isolated  from the rest of the  field (see here a singled out larger size version,  https://tinyurl.com/ybtof269 ).
We see in fig.6(a) https://tinyurl.com/y7kb7kjc  the linear  xy axes plot of  the decay of the prototype’s z -axis field with  distance.
Fig.6(b) https://tinyurl.com/yde5bf42  shows the   normalized values version plot to the inverse square distance.
Similar fig.6(c) https://tinyurl.com/y7hcp2cl  shows the  normalized values to the inverse  cube with distance.
We used a ferrite magnet which is much less  strong than neodymium magnets  so that we get comparab le  field strength values at the same distances , see fig.7(a)  https://tinyurl.com/yayggfrb  .

As expected we see in fig.7(b)  https://tinyurl.com/yaqnh4ks  of the normalized  inverse cube  values, an almost perfectly straight line, therefore a normal  dipole magnet’s field decay  complies with the inverse  cube  law with distance as measured thus the field decays  exponentially with dista nce.

Furthermore,  in fig.7(c)  https://tinyurl.com/yaz7m86p  of the inverse square  normalized plot, we see that the values deviate clearly  and  curve out from a straight  line and therefore do not comply  with an inve rse square with distance decay.
